I am not sure why people think V6 will be less decentralized. I suppose this could be the more technical changes being emphasized in the whitepaper; I will make sure to address these concerns on novelty. 

I want this to be clear, this change **expands** our ability to decentralize the subnet. 

Currently it is very expensive to validate the subnet, which limits the number of people who could feasibly run a validator. At the beginning of Bittensor, the reason for the 50/50 split between the miners and validators was to incentivize people to validate.. With the new verification mechanism being introduced, it would be feasible to validate the subnet on a raspberry pi at your house. 

While decentralized competitions are incredible at stat-maxxing, we need to be conscious about increasing the capabilities of the subnet while not sacrificing security or introducing exploits. This is where the TVM comes in. 

Instead of validating the work directly using log probs or hidden states, we can cryptographically verify the environment the work was performed in. The benefit here is that we can run different kinds of workloads using the same verification mechanism with the same security guarantees.

I hope this was clarifying 🙏  keep pushing  :pushing_tao:

I think there is a big misconception in bittensor in that the goal is decentralization. I don't think decentralization is something to strive for; I think the goal is to make a system where **participation is permissionless**. for me, this is what I think bittensors true goal is. its creating permissionless economical incentive structures where anyone can participate. I don't believe there is any virtue in being decentralized for the sake of decentralization.

Indeed, targon will become a zero-threshold system, but the goal of sn will not be better model development, because your TVM is not for model service, but only for zero-threshold hardware competition service.
